<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-478-110  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 478 110.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 31 1989 v6 n30 p55(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bridge 1.1 helps integrate applications under Windows. (fromSoftbridge Microsystems Corp.) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Softbridge Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Bridge 1.1 (Computer program) (product introduction)Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;The recently announced Bridge version 1.1 from Softbridge Microsystems Corp.andO;contains more than 25 new features designed to make it easier for users tointegrate multiple applications under Microsoft Windows.andM;&quot;Bridge gave us the capability to write Windows programs without using theWindows Software Developers Kit,&quot; said Phillip Adams, a seniorprogrammer-analyst with Fourth Generation Technology Inc., of San Diego, whoused Bridge to integrate three PC software packages.andM;Adams' firm used the Bridge batch-programming language to bring Samna Corp.'sAmi word processor, FormsMaker Software Inc.'s Horizon forms-productionpackage and Digital Communications Associates Inc.'s Windows Linkmicro-to-mainframe communications package together in a single environment.andM;Developers use the Bridge batch language in much the same way as the DOScommand language on the PC, but the batch language can automate theconstruction of Windows menus, dialog boxes and file functions, and canautomate calls to Windows dynamic link libraries, Adams said.andM;The Bridge product line includes the Bridge Tool Kit, which contains thebatch language, and the Bridge/386 and Bridge/286 run-time modules.andP;  The newversion gives developers the ability to define dialog boxes with no pushbuttons, which lets them produce automated routines that display companylogos, copyright notices or instructions to users.andM;Bridge/386 runs on 386 machines running Windows 386.andP;  Bridge/286 runs underWindows 286.andP;  The Bridge products are also compatible with MS-DOS 3.0 orlater, and Windows 2.0.andP;  The Bridge Tool Kit costs $695.andP;  Run-time licensesfor Bridge/386 and Bridge/286 start at $125 each.andM;Softbridge plans to mail free version 1.1 upgrades to all registered users ofBridge 1.0 by July 31.andP;  Contact Softbridge in Cambridge, Mass., at (617)576-2257.andO;</TEXT></DOC>